The general form of the nth term can be expressed as: \[ \text{Term } n = \left( \frac{10^n - 1}{9} \right) \times 10^{n+1} + 2 \times 10^n + \left( \frac{10^n - 1}{9} \right) \] Simplifying this expression, we find that each term can be factored as: \[ \text{Term } n = \left( \frac{10^{n+1} - 1}{9} \right) \times (10^n + 1) \] This factorization shows that each term is a product of two numbers: one is a number consisting of \( n+1 \) ones, and the other is a number of the form \( 10^n + 1 \). Both factors are composite for \( n \geq 1 \) except when \( n = 1 \), where the term is \( 121 = 11^2 \), which is also composite. Checking each of the first ten terms: 1. \( 121 = 11^2 \) (composite) 2. \( 11211 = 111 \times 101 \) (composite) 3. \( 1112111 = 1111 \times 1001 \) (composite) 4. \( 111121111 = 11111 \times 10001 \) (composite) 5. \( 11111211111 = 111111 \times 100001 \) (composite) 6. \( 1111112111111 = 1111111 \times 1000001 \) (composite) 7. \( 111111121111111 = 11111111 \times 10000001 \) (composite) 8. \( 11111111211111111 = 111111111 \times 100000001 \) (composite) 9. \( 1111111112111111111 = 1111111111 \times 1000000001 \) (composite) 10. \( 111111111121111111111 = 11111111111 \times 10000000001 \) (composite) All terms are composite, so the number of prime numbers among the first ten terms is: \[ \boxed{0} \]
